ICEbox R Package

Krystian Igras
07/11/2017

Background

  • D - observations of random variables \( X = (X1, \ldots, X_{N}) \) and \( Y \).
    \( X \) and \( Y \) related via unknown \( \ f \), \( Y = f(X) \).
  • Supervised learning algorithm B to estimate funciton \( f \).

Background

\( D + B \rightarrow \hat{f} \),

where \( \ \hat{f} \) estimates \( f \)

Issue

Understand how some variables \( X_{i} \) affects prediction of \( Y \).

Idea

Extraction of \( f_{S}(x_{S}) = \mathbb{E}[f(x_{S}, x_{C})|x_{C}] \)
\( S \) are indexes of interesting variables, C - remaining ones.

Approach

Estimation:

\( \hat{f}_{S} (x_{S}) = \frac{1}{N} \Sigma_{i=1}^{N} \hat{f} (x_{S}, y_{C_{i}}) \)

PDP

Partial dependence plot - plot of estimated function \( \hat{f}_{S} \).

R implementation

Package: pdp

Usage:

Compute function:
partial(object, ...)

Plot function:
plotPartial(x, ...)

Example 1

Model: \( Y = 0.2 X_{1} - 5 X_{2} + 10 X_{2} \mathbb{1}_{X_{3}>0} + \varepsilon \)
\( \varepsilon \sim^{iid} \mathcal{N}(0,1), \ X_{i} \sim^{iid} U(-1,1) \)

R code:

gbm_mod = gbm(y ~ ., data = Xy, n.tree = 500,
              interaction.depth = 3, shrinkage = 0.1, cv.folds = 5)
ntree = gbm.perf(gbm_mod, method = "cv")

pdp_fun <- partial(gbm_mod, pred.var = "x_2", n.trees = ntree, pred.grid = data.frame(x_2 = Xy$x_2))

plot(Xy$x_2, Xy$y, xlab = "x_2", ylab = "y")
plotPartial(pdp_fun)

Example 1 - result

New Approach

Extract components of \( \hat{f}_{S} \), and plot them!

ICE curve

Individual conditional expectation (ICE) curve: \[ \hat{f^{i}_{S}}(x_{S}) = \hat{f_{S}}(x_{S}, x_{C_{i}}) \] \( i = 1, \ldots, N \)

R implementation

Package: ICEbox

Usage:

Compute functions:
ice(object, X, predictor, ...)

And just plot result.

Example 1 - ICE version

library(ICEbox)
gbm.ice = ice(gbm_mod, interaction_ex_data$X, predictor = "x_2",
              predictfcn = function(object, newdata){predict(object, newdata, n.tree = ntree)},
              frac_to_build = 1, verbose = FALSE)

plot(gbm.ice, x_quantile = F, plot_pdp = T, frac_to_plot = 0.05)

Boston Housing Data - ICE

X = Boston
y = X$medv
X$medv = NULL

rf_mod = randomForest(X, y)
rf.ice = ice(rf_mod, X, y, predictor = "age", frac_to_build = 1, verbose = FALSE)

par(mar = c(4.3, 4, 0.1, 0.3))
plot(rf.ice, plot_pdp = TRUE, frac_to_plot = 1)

Boston Housing Data - c-ICE

par(mar = c(4.3, 4, 0.1, 2.3))
plot(rf.ice, plot_pdp = TRUE, centered = TRUE)

Boston Housing Data - second feature

rf.ice$Xice$I_rm = ifelse(rf.ice$Xice$rm > 6.2, 1, 0)

colorvec = ifelse(rf.ice$Xice$I_rm == 1, "orange", "black")

par(mar = c(4.3, 4, 0.1, 2.3))
plot(rf.ice, frac_to_plot = 1, centered = TRUE, prop_range_y = TRUE, plot_orig_pts_preds = T, color_by = "I_rm",
     colorvec = colorvec)

d-ICE

Boston Housing Data - d-ICE

rf.dice = dice(rf.ice)

par(mar = c(4.3, 4, 0.5, 2.3))
plot(rf.dice)

Additivity Assessment

Model:

Algorithm: GAM.

Additivity Assessment

gam_mod = gam(y~s(x_1)+s(x_2)+s(x_1*x_2),data=Xy)

gam.ice = ice(gam_mod, X, predictor = 1, frac_to_build = 1, verbose = FALSE)

gam.dice = dice(gam.ice)

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(gam.ice, x_quantile = F, plot_pdp = T, frac_to_plot = 1)
plot(gam.dice, x_quantile = F, plot_dpdp = T, frac_to_plot = 1)

Finding interactions and regions of interactions

gbm.ice = ice(gbm_mod, X, predictor = "x_3",
              predictfcn = function(object, newdata){predict(object, newdata, n.tree = ntree)},
              frac_to_build = 1, verbose = FALSE)

gbm.dice = dice(gbm.ice)

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(gbm.ice, x_quantile = F, plot_pdp = T, frac_to_plot = 0.05)
plot(gbm.dice, plot_orig_pts_deriv = FALSE)
